refully chosen j-invariants that produce correlated group orders—if one curve's group order has a useful factorization, the others might too.\n\nWait, that's not right. The group orders of different elliptic curves over the same field actually vary randomly within the Hasse interval, so there's no useful correlation to exploit there.\n\nLet me step back and commit to a concrete approach: I'll build a hybrid method combining lattice-based polynomial selection with batch GCD techniques and random smooth products. The lattice reduction part optimizes polynomial choices in low dimensions to find values with better smoothness properties, while the batch GCD component handles multiple candidates efficiently.\n\nActually, I should just implement a straightforward relation finder and test it empirically. The core idea is to sample random values, trial-divide them against a factor base of small primes, keep both fully smooth relations and partial relations with one or two large cofactors, then use batch GCD to merge partials by finding shared large primes, apply cycle-finding to construct complete relations, and finally run Gaussian elimination to extract the dependency that gives me the factorization.\n\nI realize this is essentially Dixon's algorithm with large prime variation—a known method, but the real value is in testing multiple candidate generation strategies (polynomial evaluation, random squares, lattice-based constructions, smooth products) and seeing which performs best in practice, rather than just reimplementing a single standard approach.\n\nI'm going to build a factoring framework with pluggable relation-finding strategies, batch GCD for efficient cofactor matching, and empirical benchmarking to guide which approach scales best. My novel contribution is the \"Smooth product residues\" strategy: instead of sieving, I'll enumerate products of factor base primes in a range near √N and test their residues for smoothness.\n\nImplementing the core infrastructure now...\n\nThe key advantage of this approach is that P is guaranteed smooth by construction, so I only need to check if R = P² - N is B-smooth. The size of R scales roughly as 2√N divided by the Dickman function ρ(u), which determines how rare smooth numbers are at that size.\n\nThis is actually larger than what quadratic sieve achieves with its best candidates, making single smooth products worse than QS. However, I can enumerate many smooth numbers near √N, and the k-th closest one gives a residue that scales with k divided by the density of smooth numbers—which is essentially equivalent to what the quadratic sieve does when sieving. The difference is just perspective: QS tests whether polynomial values are smooth, while here I'm testing whether smooth numbers themselves produce smooth residues when squared and reduced modulo N.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. If S is a smooth number near √N, say S = √N + t, then S² - N = 2√N·t + t². For small values of t, this expression depends on whether the product of these factors is smooth, not just whether individual pieces are.\n\nThe key insight is that the smooth values of t (where √N + t is smooth) correspond exactly to the quadratic sieve hits. So when I test whether S² - N is smooth, I'm essentially doing the same smoothness testing as the quadratic sieve does on f(x) = 2√N·x + x². The two approaches are fundamentally equivalent — just parametrized differently.\n\nThe only real difference with SPR would be if I could enumerate smooth numbers in a clever order and batch-test them with GCD operations, but that doesn't actually improve the asymptotic complexity. I need to stop second-guessing myself and just implement something concrete, even if it only reaches L[1/2] complexity.\n\nI'm going to build a factoring engine with multiple relation-finding strategies — smooth number hunting near √N, lattice-enhanced candidate generation using LLL, and random square reduction — then systematically compare which one sca