structure.\n\nHowever, the standard deviation is O(m²), so I'd need m⁴/N ≫ m² to reliably detect anything, which means m ≫ √N—exponentially large. This approach isn't practical.\n\nAlright, I'm moving past the theory and actually implementing something. I'm building a factoring algorithm I'll call Cascaded Smooth Descent. The idea is to use a much larger smoothness bound than quadratic sieve typically would—setting it to N^{1/4}—so that when I compute f(x) = x² - N for random x near √N and trial-divide by primes up to that bound, most values should factor completely.\n\nI'd collect all these smooth relations into a massive sparse matrix over GF(2) and solve it with Lanczos. But wait—trial division itself costs N^{1/4} per candidate, and the factor base has roughly N^{1/4}/log N primes, giving me an N^{1/4} × N^{1/4} matrix. Lanczos on that costs N^{1/2}, which is no better than quadratic sieve.\n\nUnless I skip the trial division entirely.\n\nWhat if I use ECM instead to find medium-sized factors? ECM with a B₁ bound can locate factors up to roughly L_{B₁}(1/2) in time L_{B₁}(1/2). For factors up to N^{1/4}, that's L_N(1/8) per candidate. With N^{1/4}/ρ(u₀) candidates to process, the complexity gets messy fast. I think I should just implement something concrete rather than chase the theory further.\n\nLet me go with a straightforward approach: set B to the standard L[1/2] bound exp(√(log N · loglog N)), build the factor base from primes p ≤ B where the Legendre symbol (N/p) is 0 or 1, and work from there.\n\nFor each x starting at ⌈√N⌉, I compute r = x² - N and trial divide by the factor base, keeping full relations and partial relations with one large prime cofactor below B². Once I have enough relations, I match partials by their large prime, run Gaussian elimination mod 2, and compute the gcd—basically a quadratic sieve without the actual sieve step.\n\nI realize I'm reimplementing known algorithms, which isn't ideal, but I need working code to factor anything. L