g—in the null vector computation, I'm accumulating X by multiplying the x values and reducing modulo N at each step, but I'm computing Y differently with the prime powers. Let me check the actual code...\n\nFixing the accumulation logic... I'm checking whether the product of these two values is a perfect square—it should be if the GF(2) vectors are identical, since that means all prime exponents in the product sum to even numbers. Let me verify this by computing val_0 * val_1 and checking if it's a perfect square.\n\nNow I need to compute the GCD of x_0*x_1 minus the square root of that product with N, which should give me a factor. The numbers involved are huge (30+ digits), so I'll need to test this with arbitrary precision arithmetic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":298,"cache_read_input_tokens":158790,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":298},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"bf9419ba-4b07-462a-8366-754324f149a1"}
