actor base, so the GF(2) vector should have 1s at the positions of odd exponents and 0s elsewhere.\n\nThe real issue is that the factor base only includes primes where N is a quadratic residue, so the indices aren't sequential. If a prime in the factorization isn't in the factor base, trial division will leave it in the cofactor, and that relation should be marked as partial rather than full.\n\nBut the relation checks out perfectly — the reconstructed value matches exactly and the cofactor is 1, which means all the prime factors are accounted for in the factor base and their exponents are being tracked correctly. So the GF(2) vector should be accurate. Let me print out the vectors for the first couple of full relations to verify they're what I expect.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3147,"cache_read_input_tokens":159088,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3147},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"3cd1a644-4f94-4d84-bac4-842a1039eb72"}
