rds should be zero since we never found a pivot there, but rows before rank might still have 1s from earlier operations.\n\nThe key insight is that during elimination, XOR operations modify entire rows across all columns, not just the current one being processed, so non-pivot columns in earlier rows can accumulate values from these cascading operations. we look for a pivot among rows rank..n-1, we find none. This means all rows rank..n-1 have 0 in column k. But these zeros might be the result of XOR operations from earlier column eliminations.\n\nAfter ALL columns are processed: rows rank..n-1 have 0 in every column 0..m-1. This is because:\n- For pivot columns: the elimination ensured 0.\n- For non-pivot columns: no row rank..n-1 had a 1 (because we searched and found none). ✓\n\nSo the null vectors should be correct — all zeros in the exponent part.\n\nBut wait — there's a subtle issue with the column ordering! If column j is a non-pivot column but row k < rank has a 1 in column j, then during elimination of a later column j', the XOR of row k into another row might put a 1 back in column j for some other row. But this other row is already below the current rank, so the reduced row echelon form should still work correctly. After processing all columns, the null rows really are all zeros in the first m columns.\n\nLet me verify this directly by adding a check that the null rows are truly zero in the exponent part, and then print which two relations the first null vector combines to verify their product is a perfect square.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":401,"cache_read_input_tokens":164227,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":401},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"cfb6def6-d655-4e48-84b2-5b8d