{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013YaFFSMhkL8bw65jfTrP36","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Very interesting data. With proper factor base sizes:\n\n| Digits | FB size | Fully smooth | 1LP | 2LP | Shared factor rate |\n|--------|---------|-------------|-----|-----|-------------------|\n| 40     | 1854    | 33 (0.004%) | 1884 (0.25%) | 161456 (21.5%) | 11.3% |\n| 50     | 4096*   | 6 (0.001%)  | 270 (0.04%) | 28571 (3.8%) | 4.0% |\n\n\n| 60     | 4096*   | 1 (0.0001%)  | 26 (0.003%) | 4272 (0.57%) | 0.93% |\n\n*Note: FB was capped at 4096 for 50 and 60 digit, so those are suboptimal.\n\nThe shared factor rate drops dramatically as numbers get larger—from 11.3% down to less than 1%—which tells me batch GCD matching becomes increasingly ineffective at scale and can't improve the asymptotic complexity. Two-large-prime relations dominate the landscape, vastly outnumbering both fully smooth and one-large-prime relations.\n\nNow I'm examining how the smoothness probability scales with the factor base size. The fully smooth rate at 40 digits is around 21.5%, but when I look at the actual fully smooth numbers, they're only 0.004%—a massive gap that suggests algorithms tolerating multiple large primes would have much better constants. As the digit count increases, the two-large-prime count drops consistently, which aligns with what I'd expect from L[1/2] scaling for smoothness probabilities.\n\nLet me work through the scaling math using the Dickman function. For 40 digits, the value size is roughly 10^20, the factor base tops out around 34589, so the smoothness parameter u comes out to about 4.4.\n\nWhen I calculate what ρ(4.4) predicts, I get around 0.003, which would mean roughly 2250 smooth values in my 750000 candidates—but I only found 33. That's a huge discrepancy, likely because my sieve range doesn't capture enough candidates in the sweet spot where values stay small enough to be smooth.\n\nThe real takeaway here is that batch GCD with cofactor matching achieves roughly a 10% collision rate at 40 digits, dropping to about 1% at 60 digits—a constant-factor win but nothing that changes the asymptotic complexity. This aligns with what the existing analysis shows: these techniques improve the constants but don't shift the L-exponent itself. To actually improve the exponent, I'd need something fundamentally different, like using number fields to reduce the value size below √N.\n\nSo instead of chasing marginal improvements, let me test whether a \"progressive descent\" strategy could work in practice. The idea is to collect relations with arbitrary-sized cofactors and then recursively factor them using ECM, where the descent cost for a cofactor C scales as L_C(1/2). If the total descent cost across all relations ends up cheaper than finding additional fully smooth relations, this could yield a real practical speedup. For my 40-digit test case with 1854 primes in the factor base, I'm getting 33 fully smooth relations plus thousands of partial relations—so the question is whether descending those partials beats the cost of sieving harder.\n\nLooking at the numbers: getting to 1854 fully smooth relations would require roughly 42 million candidates, which is expensive. But I could instead use the 1884 one-large-prime relations through matching (yielding around 770 matches), combine those with the 33 fully smooth, and then tackle the remaining gap using two-large-prime relations where I apply ECM descent. For the one-large-prime relations, the cofactors are already prime so no descent is needed. For the two-large-prime relations, I'd use ECM to factor composite cofactors and see if that's faster than the alternative.\n\nECM can split 30-bit numbers in microseconds, so processing 160K cofactors takes under a second. After factoring, about 11.3% of the cofactors share factors across relations, which gives me roughly 9000 additional combined relations from matching. That brings the total to around 10000 relations—far more than the 1854 I actually need. So for 40-digit numbers, the two-large-prime approach is extremely efficient.\n\nBut the real question is whether I can push further with three or more large primes. For 3LP relations, I'd need cofactors below B³ ≈ 10^13.5. Looking at the histogram data, I'm adding up how many candidates fall into that range across all the bit-length buckets.\n\nThat gives me about 22,763 candidates out of 750,000—roughly 3%. The challenge is that even though these cofactors are small enough in theory, they need to factor into three primes each under the bound of ~34,589. A cofactor around 10^13 would require three primes averaging around 2,500, but 2,500³ is only about 1.5×10^10, far short of what I need. So most of these cofactors won't actually split into three small primes, making them unusable for 3LP relations.\n\nLooking at the math, only about 4% of the cofactors will split into primes below the bound, leaving me with maybe 900 usable 3LP relations. Each relation has three large primes, creating a graph with roughly 2,700 prime vertices and 900 hyperedges. Finding cycles in this structure is possible but significantly harder than with 2LP relations.\n\nI should focus on implementing something practical that tests how this scales, then update my notes with what I've learned and build a fast factoring approach using the best available techniques.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2404,"cache_read_input_tokens":201490,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2404},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"a754b96c-863c-4995-a918-c5df6e05bb0c"}
