{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0192G6Li2Vn5YXpYjTEJ4sho","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me focus on a genuinely novel direction. Based on my analysis, the fundamental bottleneck is:\n- Smooth numbers near √N have probability ρ(u) where u = log(√N)/log(B)\n- No candidate generation strategy can change this for QS-style polynomials\n- The ONLY known way to beat L[1/2] is to use algebraic structures giving smaller values (NFS → L[1/3])\n\nLet me try something different: **Simplified NFS for medium-sized numbers** (50-80 digits). Standard NFS is only used above ~100 digits because of overhead, but a simplified version might work for smaller numbers."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":124,"cache_read_input_tokens":209188,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":124},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"704d5198-4ee7-40a5-b237-0d04f05bfb17"}
