{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SpgoaRAWbKjQZzFyXDAvjJ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"novel integer factoring algorithm breakthrough 2024 2025 sub-exponential\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"A Novel Hybrid Quantum Circuit for Integer Factorization: End-to-End Evaluation in Simulation and Real Quantum Hardware[v4] | Preprints.org\",\"url\":\"https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202510.1649\"},{\"title\":\"General integer factorization algorithm based on Ising machine | EPJ Quantum Technology | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1140/epjqt/s40507-025-00449-9\"},{\"title\":\"A Novel Approach to Integer Factorization: A Paradigm in Cryptography - Ilkhom - 2025 - Concurrency and Computation: Practice and Experience - Wiley Online Library\",\"url\":\"https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/cpe.8365\"},{\"title\":\"A First Successful Factorization of RSA-2048 Integer by D-Wave Quantum Computer\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciopen.com/article/10.26599/TST.2024.9010028\"},{\"title\":\"Shor’s Algorithm – Quantum Computing’s Breakthrough in Factoring | SpinQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.spinquanta.com/news-detail/Shor-s-Algorithm-Quantum-Computing-s-Breakthrough-in-Factoring\"},{\"title\":\"The state of the art in integer factoring and breaking public key cryptography\",\"url\":\"https://hal.science/hal-03691141v1/document\"},{\"title\":\"Integer factorization - Algorithms for Competitive Programming\",\"url\":\"https://cp-algorithms.com/algebra/factorization.html\"},{\"title\":\"Integer factorization - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization\"},{\"title\":\"Effective prime factorization via quantum annealing by modular locally-structured embedding | Scientific Reports\",\"url\":\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-024-53708-7\"},{\"title\":\"New Subexponential Algorithms for Factoring in SL(2,F2n)\",\"url\":\"https://eprint.iacr.org/2011/598.pdf\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of what the search results reveal about recent developments in integer factoring algorithms (2024–2025):\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**No major classical sub-exponential breakthrough found.** The search results do not indicate a novel classical algorithm that fundamentally improves upon the sub-exponential complexity of the General Number Field Sieve (GNFS) during 2024–2025.\n\n### Current State of Classical Factoring\n- As of 2022, the algorithm with the best theoretical asymptotic running time is the General Number Field Sieve (GNFS), first published in 1993. For current computers, GNFS remains the best published algorithm for large numbers (more than about 400 bits).\n- While the general asymptotic running time for the number field sieve has not been improved since the algorithm was developed in the early 1990s, there has been algorithmic progress that has had a dramatic impact on the actual running time of the algorithm.\n- Progress in classical cryptanalysis sometimes requires as little as a single mathematical insight and some software development. There is no evidence that the current running time of the number field sieve is optimal for factoring.\n\n### Recent Work (2024–2025) — Primarily Quantum/Hybrid Approaches\n\n1. **Ising Machine-Based Factoring (2025):** A study proposed a universal algorithm for integer factorization based on Ising machines by transforming the problem into a Quadratic Unconstrained Binary Optimization (QUBO) formulation. The team successfully factored a 22-bit integer using 118 qubits on the D-Wave quantum computing platform.\n\n2. **D-Wave RSA-2048 Claim (2024–2025):** Researchers attempted to transform the integer factorization problem in RSA attacks into a combinatorial optimization problem using the QA algorithm of D-Wave quantum computer, and attacked RSA-2048 composed of a class of special integers.\n\n3. **Quantum Annealing Factorization (2024):** A paper in *Scientific Reports* investigated novel techniques to solve prime factorization by quantum annealing, presenting a very-compact modular encoding of a multiplier circuit into D-Wave QA devices.\n\n4. **Toom-Cook-Based Approach (2025):** A paper proposed a solution to the factorization problem in cryptographic systems by leveraging the steps of the Toom-Cook algorithm for large-number multiplication. This approach can factor a 200-bit number, with performance varying depending on memory and processing power.\n\n5. **Hybrid Quantum Circuit (2025):** A hybrid classical-quantum algorithm using a classical modular exponentiation subroutine with a Quantum Number Theoretic Transform (QNTT) circuit was proposed to reduce quantum resources relative to Shor's algorithm.\n\n### Bottom Line\n\nClassical factoring remains at sub-exponential time (exp((log N)^(1/3)) for GNFS), while Shor's algorithm offers polynomial time O((log N)^3) — but only on a quantum computer. No classical breakthrough achieving better-than-GNFS sub-exponential complexity appears to have been published in 2024 or 2025 based on these search results. The recent activity has been concentrated on **quantum and hybrid quantum-classical** approaches, none of which yet scale to cryptographically relevant sizes.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"d845e00a-7891-4b84-89dd-7c8fff00c4f4","timestamp":"2026-03-24T03:00:34.713Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"novel integer factoring algorithm breakthrough 2024 2025 sub-exponential","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_017pzi8HhWbzeVtQhPzGSmXG","content":[{"title":"A Novel Hybrid Quantum Circuit for Integer Factorization: End-to-End Evaluation in Simulation and Real Quantum Hardware[v4] | Preprints.org","url":"https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202510.1649"},{"title":"General integer factorization algorithm based on Ising machine | EPJ Quantum Technology | Sp