{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QZXDYKKrEc4rXhffLCieAG","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Schnorr lattice factoring improved 2023 2024 practical results\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Experimental Analysis of Integer Factorization Methods Using Lattices | Advances in Information and Computer Security\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1007/978-981-97-7737-2_8\"},{\"title\":\"Experimental Analysis of Integer Factorization Methods Using Lattices | SpringerLink\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-981-97-7737-2_8\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - lducas/SchnorrGate: Testing Schnorr's factorization claim in Sage · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/lducas/SchnorrGate\"},{\"title\":\"Lattice basis reduction: Improved practical algorithms and solving subset sum problems | Mathematical Programming | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01581144\"},{\"title\":\"Factoring integers via Schnorr’s algorithm assisted with VQE\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2411.16632v1\"},{\"title\":\"Factoring Integers via Schnorr’s Algorithm Assisted with VQE | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-031-90200-0_7\"},{\"title\":\"arXiv:2307.09651v2 [quant-ph] 21 Jul 2023\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2307.09651\"},{\"title\":\"Lattice basis reduction: Improved practical algorithms and solving subset sum problems | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/3-540-54458-5_51\"},{\"title\":\"On Schnorr-Adleman lattice | IEEE Conference Publication | IEEE Xplore\",\"url\":\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1236457/\"},{\"title\":\"Factoring integers via Schnorr's algorithm assisted with VQE | alphaXiv\",\"url\":\"https://www.alphaxiv.org/overview/2411.16632v1\"}]\n\nHere is a summary of the recent research on Schnorr's lattice-based factoring approach and practical results from 2023–2024:\n\n## Background\n\nSince 1991, Schnorr has proposed methods using lattices for solving the integer factorization problem whose hardness supports the security of the RSA cryptosystem. The core idea reduces factoring to solving the Closest Vector Problem (CVP) or Shortest Vector Problem (SVP) on specially constructed lattices. In 2021, a follow-up work by Schnorr claimed to reduce the required dimension of the lattice, but the claims in the paper are highly debated, and most experts believe the lattice dimension required is much larger than what is claimed.\n\n## Key Developments (2022–2024)\n\n### Yan et al. (2022) — Quantum-assisted Schnorr factoring\nIn 2022, Yan et al. proposed a modification of Schnorr's lattices and reported numerical experiments by an optimization method using quantum computation. They claimed that one can break RSA 2048 using only 372 qubits.\n\n### Khattar & Yosri (2023) — Refuting the quantum claims\nTheir implementation showed that the claimed sublinear lattice dimension for the hybrid quantum+classical version of Schnorr's algorithm successfully factors integers only up to 70 bits and fails to find enough factoring relations for random 80-bit integers and beyond. They showed that even if we had a perfect quantum optimizer (instead of a heuristic like QAOA), the proposed claims don't hold true.\n\n### Yamaguchi et al. (2023) — Classical annealing approach\nYamaguchi et al. reported that they succeeded in factoring RSA-type composite numbers of at most 55 bits based on Yan et al.'s modification, using classical annealing calculation.\n\n### Sato, Auzemery, Katayama & Yasuda — IWSEC 2024\nThey reported experimental results of integer factorization methods using lattices in classical computing, analyzing the structure of Schnorr's lattices to select suitable parameters and applying existing lattice algorithms for finding smooth relations. They reported the running time of integer factorization using lattices for RSA-type composite numbers of at most 90 bits.\n\n### Cano et al. (2024) — VQE-assisted Schnorr factoring\nThis research explores a hybrid quantum-classical approach by integrating the Variational Quantum Eigensolver (VQE) into Schnorr's algorithm. The work successfully factored the small integer N=1961 under specific classical pre-processing conditions, but faced challenges with scalability for larger integers.\n\n## Expert Consensus\n\nLéo Ducas's personal study of this approach suggested that it requires solving SVP in dimensions beyond reasonable, leading to a factorization algorithm much slower than the state of the art. His impression is that this is the consensus among experts having spent some time on it as well. The claim of polynomial-time factoring was announced at Eurocrypt 2009 and has so far not been published at a peer-reviewed conference or journal.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe practical results remain very modest — factoring only up to **55–90 bit** integers depending on the method, which is far from threatening real-world RSA (2048-bit). Both classical and quantum-assisted implementations of Schnorr's lattice approach have failed to scale to cryptographically relevant sizes, and the expert consensus remains that the approach does not currently offer a practical path to breaking RSA.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"4d25c4e2-f6b9-48ff-8e97-ad8d6fa11f57","timestamp":"2026-03-24T03:01:09.107Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"Schnorr lattice factoring improved 2023 2024 practical results","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Sk81pb3atDoB79Wjs2ga18","content":[{"title":"Experimental Analysis of Integer Factorization Methods Using Lattices | Advances in Information and Computer Security","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1007/978-981-97-7737-2_8"},{"title":"Experimental Analysis of Integer Factorization Methods Using Lattices | SpringerLink","url":"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-981-97-7737-2_8"},{"title":"GitHub - lducas/SchnorrGate: Testing Schnorr's factorization claim in Sage · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/lducas/SchnorrGate"},{"title":"Lattice basis reduction: Improved practical algorithms and solving subset sum problems | Mathematical Programming | Springer Nature Link","url":"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01581144"},{"title":"Factoring integers via Schnorr’s algorithm assisted with VQE","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2411.16632v1"},{"title":"Factoring Integers via Schnorr’s Algorithm Assisted with VQE | Springer Nature Link","url":"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-031-90200-0_7"},{"title":"arXiv:2307.09651v2 [quant-ph] 21 Jul 2023","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2307.09651"},{"title":"Lattice basis reduction: Improved practical algorithms and solving subset sum problems | Springer Nature Link","url":"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/3-540-54458-5_51"},{"title":"On Schnorr-Adleman lattice | IEEE Conference Publication | IEEE Xplore","url":"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1236457/"},{"title":"Factoring integers via Schnorr's algorithm assisted with VQE | alphaXiv","url":"https://www.alphaxiv.org/overview/2411.16632v1"}]},"Here is a summary of the recent research on Schnorr's lattice-based factoring approach and practical results from 2023–2024:\n\n## Background\n\nSince 1991, Schnorr has proposed methods using lattices for solving the integer factorization problem whose hardness supports the security of the RSA cryptosystem. The core idea reduces factoring to solving the Closest Vector Problem (CVP) or Shortest Vector Problem (SVP) on specially constructed lattices. In 2021, a follow-up work by Schnorr claimed to reduce the required dimension of the lattice, but the claims in the paper are highly debated, and most experts believe the lattice dimension required is much larger than what is claimed.\n\n## Key Developments (2022–2024)\n\n### Yan et al. (2022) — Quantum-assisted Schnorr factoring\nIn 2022, Yan et al. proposed a modification of Schnorr's lattices and reported numerical experiments by an optimization method using quantum computation. They claimed that one can break RSA 2048 using only 372 qubits.\n\n### Khattar & Yosri (2023) — Refuting the quantum claims\nTheir implementation showed that the claimed sublinear lattice dimension for the hybrid quantum+classical version of Schnorr's algorithm successfully factors integers only up to 70 bits and fails to find enough factoring relations for random 80-bit integers and beyond. They showed that even if we had a perfect quantum optimizer (instead of a heuristic like QAOA), the proposed claims don't hold true.\n\n### Yamaguchi et al. (2023) — Classical annealing approach\nYamaguchi et al. reported that they succeeded in factoring RSA-type composite numbers of at most 55 bits based on Yan et al.'s modification, using classical annealing calculation.\n\n### Sato, Auzemery, Katayama & Yasuda — IWSEC 2024\nThey reported experimental results of integer factorization methods using lattices in classical computing, analyzing the structure of Schnorr's lattices to select suitable parameters and applying existing lattice algorithms for finding smooth relations. They reported the running time of integer factorization using lattices for RSA-type composite numbers of at most 90 bits.\n\n### Cano et al. (2024) — VQE-assisted Schnorr factoring\nThis research explores a hybrid quantum-classical approach by integrating the Variational Quantum Eigensolver (VQE) into Schnorr's algorithm. The work successfully factored the small integer N=1961 under specific classical pre-processing conditions, but faced challenges with scalability for larger integers.\n\n## Expert Consensus\n\nLéo Ducas's personal study of this approach suggested that it requires solving SVP in dimensions beyond reasonable, leading to a factorization algorithm much slower than the state of the art. His impression is that this is the consensus among experts having spent some time on it as well. The claim of polynomial-time factoring was announced at Eurocrypt 2009 and has so far not been published at a peer-reviewed conference or journal.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe practical results remain very modest — factoring only up to **55–90 bit** integers depending on the method, which is far from threatening real-world RSA (2048-bit). Both classical and quantum-assisted implementations of Schnorr's lattice approach have failed to scale to cryptographically relevant sizes, and the expert consensus remains that the approach does not currently offer a practical path to breaking RSA."],"durationSeconds":30.836594562999903}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01GqV2eHMpMAQtnVpteaPP36","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting - the Sato et al. IWSEC 2024 paper reports factoring up to 90-bit numbers using improved lattice methods. That's still small, but it's progress over Ducas's \"0 relations in 1000 trials\". Let me look at what they did differently.\n\nAlso interesting: the VQE + Schnorr approach factored N=1961 but didn't scale.\n\nLet me look at one more thing: what about the \"correlated norms\" direction I identified in expert.md as a new open direction.\n\nActually, let me focus on being productive. The benchmarks are running. Let me think about what CONCRETE novel experiment I can run next.\n \nSo I've confirmed that batch GCD matching only improves constants, simplified NFS isn't competitive for small numbers, and Schnorr lattice barely reaches 90 bits - there's no classical sub-L[1/3] algorithm to beat. But the \"k independent views\" idea is interesting: if I can construct k different evaluation maps for each candidate, the complexity would improve to L[1/(k+1)], whereas standard NFS only has k=2.\n\nThe real challenge is forcing independence between algebraic views. Using different evaluation points for different polynomials - like f(x₁) and g(x₂) where x₁ ≠ x₂ - could break the correlation that normally ties them together, potentially giving me genuinely independent information about the factors.\n\nIn multi-polynomial NFS, I'm exploring whether composing polynomials algebraically - like defining f₂ as an iteration of f₁ - could create a stronger structural relationship that yields better smoothness properties than just having multiple independent polynomials sharing the same root.\n\nNow I'm considering a completely different approach using multiplicative Fourier analysis over Z/NZ. The idea is that if I could compute the discrete Fourier transform of a signal encoding smooth numbers, the spectral peaks would reveal the group structure and expose the factorization - but this runs into a circular dependency since computing the DFT over Z/NZ requires already knowing the group structure.\n\nI could try using the Walsh-Hadamard transform instead, which doesn't require knowing the group structure upfront and has useful properties for boolean functions like the smoothness indicator. The WHT of the smoothness function might expose structure related to the underlying multiplicative group, but I'm not convinced this actually leads anywhere for factoring.\n\nAt this point I should stop exploring theoretical angles and focus on implementation and benchmarking. Though before I do, there's one more direction worth considering: exploiting how smooth numbers distribute across arithmetic progressions using Dirichlet's theorem.\n\nThe key insight is that if I can use the Chinese Remainder Theorem to construct values where x² - N is guaranteed to be smooth modulo multiple primes simultaneously—by choosing x ≡ ±√N (mod p) for each prime p in my factor base—then I can systematically generate smooth relations without random searching.\n\nBut this is exactly what the quadratic sieve already does through its sieving process: it identifies which x values produce f(x) divisible by many factor base primes. The CRT approach would yield the same x values, so there's no computational advantage.\n\nI keep circling back to the same realization: within the smoothness framework, quadratic and number field sieves are essentially optimal. Breaking through requires abandoning smoothness entirely.\n\nThe one direction I haven't fully explored is reformulating factoring as a Hidden Subgroup Problem, like Shor's algorithm does. Classically, HSP over Z is hard, but maybe there's a classical angle I'm missing.\n\nWhat if I embed the problem in a larger group structure? The multiplicative group (Z/NZ)* contains hidden subgroups related to the factorization, but perhaps working in a larger group like GL(2, Z/NZ) could expose the structure differently. The challenge is that this group becomes exponentially larger—computing with random elements becomes prohibitively expensive.\n\nI could try encoding the factorization as a permutation group structure in S_n, but I'd need an efficient embedding and a way to extract factoring information from the permutation group algorithms. I don't see a known construction that achieves this.\n\nI'm not making progress on this angle—let me step back and look at the actual benchmarks to ground myself in what's working.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1431,"cache_read_input_tokens":229304,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1431},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"c39ff738-af30-48c2-9b06-9a6cb7d4f78e"}
