{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01V8gMSmtMiiEtWC4eL6DcJf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"LGSH scaling:\n- 30 digits: 0.14s\n- 35 digits: 0.21s\n- 40 digits: 0.77s\n- 45 digits: 6.21s\n- 50 digits: 255s\n\nThe jump from 45 to 50 digits is dramatic (6.2 → 255 = 41x increase for 5 digits). This looks like L[1/2] scaling.\n\nLet me fit this to check. For L[1/2, c], time = exp(c * sqrt(d * ln 10 * ln(d * ln 10))):\n\n\nNow I'm computing the exponent values at different digit counts to see if they follow the expected pattern. At 30 digits I get around 17.1, at 45 digits around 21.9, and at 50 digits around 23.4.\n\nUsing these to predict time ratios, I calculate what the scaling constant c should be from the actual observed times. But when I work backwards from the data, I'm getting wildly different c values—0.79 from one ratio and 2.48 from another—which tells me the relationship isn't actually following a simple square-root scaling law.\n\nLooking at the expected performance with standard quadratic sieve constants, the 50-digit case is performing far worse than theory predicts, suggesting either poor parameter tuning in the implementation, a bug at larger sizes, or measurement overhead that doesn't scale predictably. Rather than chase down what's causing this anomaly, I should focus on what I can actually optimize.\n\nSince the 50-digit timing of 255 seconds leaves almost no room before hitting the 295-second timeout, I'm wondering if I can build a genuinely improved quadratic sieve by combining traditional candidate generation with adaptive techniques. The core idea is to start with a small initial factor base and dynamically expand it as I discover which primes appear frequently in cofactors—essentially learning the optimal factor base from the data itself rather than fixing it upfront. This way the initial sieve phase stays fast while still capturing the relations I need. effective factor base is data-driven rather than predetermined.\n\nThis is related to the \"large prime\" approach but more systematic. Instead of matching cofactors (which requires exact or GCD matches), we PROMOTE frequently-seen cofactors to the factor base.\n\nIs this novel? I haven't seen this specific approach in the literature. It's similar to \"feeding\" primes from LP matching back into the factor base, but done adaptively during sieving.\n\nLet me think about whether this helps asymptotically. The factor base size determines the smoothness bound. With a larger factor base, more numbers are smooth but the matrix is bigger. The standard optimization balances these two effects.\n\nAdaptive expansion: start with B₀ < B_optimal. Sieve cheaply. Find frequent cofactors. Add them to the factor base. The new factor base B₁ = B₀ ∪ {frequent cofactors}. Sieve again (or reuse existing data).\n\nBut wait — those frequent cofactors are large primes, bigger than B₀, so they don't actually help smooth other candidates. The only benefit is recovering relations that already have these specific cofactors. That's just LP matching reframed. So this isn't novel after all.\n\nLet me pivot to something genuinely different: testing a candidate generation strategy that doesn't rely on sequential evaluation. Instead of the standard quadratic sieve approach, I'd generate candidates by choosing pairs of factor base primes and computing products modulo N with various multipliers, then checking if the results are smooth. This would give us relations where the cofactors are already somewhat constrained by the construction.\n\nActually, that's just Dixon's method with a structured twist — not an improvement.\n\nWhat about using continued fraction convergents more creatively? Instead of testing individual convergent residues for smoothness, I could test products of residues from different convergents. The algebraic structure of the CF expansion might give these products nicer factorization properties.\n\nBut working through the algebra, the product doesn't factor in any obviously useful way.\n\nLet me step back and focus on what actually works: building a fast, clean SIQS implementation and then testing novel modifications systematically — adaptive sieve thresholds, batch GCD post-processing, ECM cofactor splitting, and SIMD polynomial evaluation. I'll measure the L-exponent impact of each change carefully.\n\nThough I'm realizing the instructions forbid reimplementing SIQS from scratch, but they do allow using existing ECM implementations.\n\nSo instead, let me work with the existing LGSH baseline and see if I can push it further. A 50-digit number takes 255 seconds — if I can make it 10x faster, I could test up to 55-60 digits. Let me examine the LGSH source code to find the actual bottlenecks.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":504,"cache_read_input_tokens":233241,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":504},"output_tokens":57,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"edde4462-56c0-4971-9d3e-eda10bd1a6be"}
