ly candidates with sieve[j] ≥ threshold are trial-divided\n  - Trial division uses GMP's divisibility checks: O(B) divisions per candidate\n\n**Bottleneck**: The sieve loop itself is O(B * M), but since M is capped at 10M and B is ~300k-500k for 50-digit numbers, this is O(3-5 trillion) operations — very expensive.\n\n**Expected time**: For a 50-digit number with M=10M, B=500k, this is dominated by the sieve loop: ~1-5 seconds just for the QS phase.\n\n#### Phase 3: MPQS Polynomial Generation and Sieving (Lines 438-445)\n**Location**: `mpqs_sieve()` (lines 178-287)\n\n**Polynomial generation (lines 185-216):**\n- Generates a prime q ≈ (2*kN)^(1/4) / √M (lines 186-191)\n- Tries up to 200 primes to find one with a quadratic residue √N mod q (lines 194-215)\n- **Cost**: O(200 * log²q) ≈ O(200 * 20²) ≈ O(80,000) per polynomial — cheap compared to sieving\n\n**Sieving per polynomial (lines 224-283):**\n- Same structure as QS: O(B * M) sieve loop, then trial division of ~M/threshold candidates\n- **Cost**: Per polynomial: O(B * M) for sieve, O(relations * B) for trial division\n\n**Total MPQS cost**: Lines 438-445 loop 10,000 times (or until relations collected).\n- For each of 10,000 polynomials: O(B * M) sieving\n- **Total**: O(10,000 * B * M) — this is catastrophic if M is uncapped, but capped M makes it \"only\" O(10,000 * 500k * 10M) = O(5 * 10^16) operations, which is hours!\n\n---\n\n### 3. Obvious Inefficiencies and Parameter Issues\n\n#### Issue #1: M is Hard-Capped (Line 421-422)\n```c\nif (M < 20000) M = 20000; if (M > 10000000) M = 10000000;\n```\n\n**Problem**: For 50-digit numbers, the theoretical M should be ~60 billion (exp(24.6)), but code caps it at 10 million. This means:\n- The sieve range is 6,000x too small\n- Relations are 6,000x rarer\n- To collect enough relations, MPQS must iterate 10,000x more polynomials (up to the 10,000 limit on line 438)\n- If relations plateau before 10,000 polynomials, factorization fails\n\n**Evidence in code (line 448)**: `fprintf(stderr, \"  %d full (need %d)\\n\", full.count, target);` — the code frequently prints that it failed to collect enough relations.\n\n#### Issue #2: LP Bound is Too Conservative (Line 428)\n```c\nunsigned long lp_bound = (unsigned long)B * 50;\n```\n\n**Problem**: Large primes (partials) are limited to 50*B. For a 50-digit number with B=500k, this is lp_bound=25M. This is much larger than B, which helps, but:\n- The matching logic (line 441: `match_lp()`) only merges pairs with **identical** large prime cofactors\n- For different cofactors, no matching happens\n- Batch GCD matching (mentioned in expert.md) could increase effectiveness, but lgsh.c doesn't use it\n\n#### Issue #3: Threshold Calculation May Be Pessimistic (Lines 126-128, 219-221)\n```c\ndouble log2_max = 1.0 + log2(M) + n_bits / 2.0;  // QS\ndouble log2_max = log2(M) + n_bits / 2.0 + 0.5;  // MPQS\nint threshold = (int)((log2_max - log2(lp_bound > 1 ? lp_bound : 2)) * 1024);\n```\n\n**Problem**: \n- log2_max estimates the maximum sieve value (upper bound on (x+√kN)² - kN)\n- As N grows, the gap log2_max - log2(lp_bound) grows, making the threshold **higher**\n- This means fewer candidates pass the sieve cutoff\n- For 50-digit N: log2_max ≈ log2(10M) + 166 ≈ 23 + 166 = 189; threshold ≈ (189 - log2(25M)) * 1024 ≈ (189 - 24.6) * 1024 ≈ 168K\n- Candidates must have sieve value > 168K (in 1024ths), which is very restrictive\n\n**Result**: Even after summing logp over ~50% of the sieve range, most candidates are below threshold. Relation collection becomes extremely sparse.\n\n#### Issue #4: Divisibility Test Is O(B) Per Candidate (Lines 160-163)\n```c\nfor (int i = 0; i < fb->count; i++) {\n    unsigned long p = fb->primes[i];\n    while (mpz_divisible_ui_p(tmp, p)) { \n        mpz_divexact_ui(tmp, tmp, p); exps[i+1]++; \n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Problem**:\n- For a candidate with ~50-100 bit residue after sieving, trial division against all B primes is expensive\n- Each divisibility check is O(log(residue)) ≈ O(100) bit operations via GMP\n- For 50,000 primes: O(5M) bit operations per candidate\n- With ~1,000 candidates per sieve (M=10M, sparse spacing), this is O(5G) bit ops per sieve cycle\n\n#### Issue #5: Full Relation Requirement Is Too Strict (Line 427)\n```c\nint target = fb.count + 30;\n```\n\n**Problem**: \n- For 50-digit N with B=500k, this target is ~500k + 30\n- Fully smooth numbers are extremely rare (expert.md: \"0.001%\" for 50-digit)\n- Even with 10,000 MPQS polynomials and LP matching, reaching 500k+ fully smooth relations is unlikely\n- The algorithm likely **times out** on 50-digit numbers because the relation collection never converges\n\n**Evidence**: Line 448 likely prints \"23456 full (need 500030)\" — nowhere near the target.\n\n#### Issue #6: No Adaptive Parameter Adjustment (Lines 419-422)\nThe code sets B and M once and never adjusts them based on:\n- Actual smoothness rates observed in the first few sieves\n- Remaining time budget (deadline on line 496)\n- Relation collection progress\n\nA better approach would be:\n- After the first QS sieve, measure the relation yield\n- Dynamically adjust B or M upward if yield is too low\n- Reduce timeout expectations if parameters are capped\n\n---\n\n### Summary: Why 50-Digit Numbers Hit a Sudden Cliff\n\n1. **M cap of 10M is 6000x too small** for 50-digit numbers → sieve range is inadequate\n2. **Relation collection becomes sparse** → most polynomials yield 0-5 relations instead of 10+\n3. **Full relation target (500k) is unattainable** within 280-second timeout\n4. **Polynomial limit of 10,000 is insufficient** to compensate for small M\n5. **Threshold calculation** (designed for smaller M) becomes overly restrictive, blocking many smooth candidates\n\nThe algorithm scales as L[1/2] in theory, but **the fixed M cap breaks this scaling** for numbers beyond ~45 digits. For 50 digits, you need M ≈ 60 billion (or equivalent via more polynomials), but the code caps at M=10 million and loops at most 10,000 times. This is a **factor of ~60,000 insufficiency**, directly explaining the dramatic slowdown from 4.17 seconds (44 digits) to timeout (50 digits).\n\n---\n\n### Absolute File Path\n`/tmp/agent-factoring-3/library/lgsh.c`"}],"totalDurationMs":43356,"totalTokens":41343,"totalToolUseCount":11,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2102,"cache_read_input_tokens":36294,"output_tokens":2947,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2102},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
