{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UXxpzVGbGuSCB9ygMV2div","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**This is a significant finding!** For 40-digit N:\n\n| Method | Both-smooth rate | NFS/QS ratio |\n|--------|-----------------|--------------|\n| QS     | 0.273%          | 1.00         |\n| NFS d=3| 0.022%          | 0.08         |\n| NFS d=4| 0.289%          | 1.06         |\n| NFS d=5| 0.717%          | **2.63**     |\n\n**NFS degree 5 gives 2.63x MORE doubly-smooth relations per candidate than QS!** This is because the norms are smaller (26.5 bits rational, 50.1 bits algebraic vs 81.8 bits for QS). The double-smoothness penalty is outweighed by the smaller norm sizes.\n\nThe 50 and 60 digit runs timed out. Let me log this result and investigate whether this advantage grows with N size."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":809,"cache_read_input_tokens":300915,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":809},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"7a178de3-ef5b-4baa-bfef-b1d3936efd91"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UXxpzVGbGuSCB9ygMV2div","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HTCiL2j1jZqhi4tXGkfsop","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat >> experiments.log << 'EOF'\n[2026-03-24 04:00:00] size: 40 | approach: alg_sieve_exp (NFS d=5 brute force) | time: 60s | notes: NFS d=5 gives 2.63x more doubly-smooth rels per candidate than QS! avg rat_norm=26.5 bits, alg_norm=50.1 bits vs QS=81.8 bits. 44 doubly-smooth from 6138 candidates. QS-style had 2 smooth from 100K. Key finding: for 40-digit N, NFS-style evaluation IS more efficient per candidate even without lattice sieving.\n[2026-03-24 04:00:00] size: 40 | approach: alg_sieve_exp (NFS d=4 brute force) | time: 30s | notes: NFS d=4 gives 1.06x — roughly equal to QS. 89 doubly-smooth from 30770.\n[2026-03-24 04:00:00] size: 40 | approach: alg_sieve_exp (NFS d=3 brute force) | time: 15s | notes: NFS d=3 gives 0.08x — worse than QS. Double-smoothness penalty dominates.\nEOF\ngit add experiments.log library/alg_sieve_exp.c && git commit -m \"NFS algebraic sieve experiment: d=5 gives 2.63x more relations/candidate than QS for 40-digit\n\nKey finding: brute-force NFS degree-5 evaluation produces 2.63x more\ndoubly-smooth relations per candidate than QS at 40 digits. Norms are\nsubstantially smaller (26+50 bits vs 82 bits). The degree-5 advantage\nshould grow with N size. This motivates implementing a proper NFS with\nat least basic line sieving for the 50-70 digit range.\" && git push 2>&1 | tail -3","description":"Commit NFS experiment results"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":809,"cache_read_input_tokens":300915,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":809},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16e