{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013W55ESp6tn1PMkSZbAE2e8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I can see: rpass=1116, apass=135, but **both=14**. Only 14 candidates pass both thresholds. Of those, only 2 are actually doubly-smooth after trial division.\n\nThe issue: the algebraic sieve has much lower accumulation (avg 4.8 vs rational avg 5.5), and the algebraic threshold (17.2) is too high relative to the max (33.3). Only 135 of 10001 positions pass the algebraic threshold.\n\nThe algebraic threshold `ane * 0.40` where `ane = deg * log(A_MAX) + log2(c_d) * log(2)` = 3 * ln(5000) + log2(c_3) * 0.693. For c_3 ≈ 2.1e7: ane = 3*8.5 + 24.3*0.693 = 25.5 + 16.8 = 42.3. athr = 42.3 * 0.40 = 16.9.\n\nThe ACTUAL algebraic norm |f_hom(a,b)| for b=1 is roughly c_d * a^d ≈ 2.1e7 * a^3 for d=3. For a=5000: norm ≈ 2.1e7 * 1.25e11 ≈ 2.6e18. log(2.6e18) = 42.4. That matches ane.\n\nFor a=100: norm ≈ 2.1e7 * 10^6 = 2.1e13. log = 30.7. \n\nThe sieve accumulates up to 33.3 (max). For a fully smooth 30-bit number, the sieve should accumulate log(30-bit-smooth-product) ≈ 20. For a 42-bit number to be smooth, we need ≈ 28. So athr=17.2 is reasonable as a LOWER BOUND (allowing for partial smoothness).\n\nThe real issue is that only 14 candidates pass BOTH thresholds, and trial division further reduces to 2. This is because the search range is too small for degree 3 at 30 digits.\n\nFrom my earlier experiment: NFS d=3 gives 0.022% rate, while d=5 gives 0.717%. Let me try d=5 instead!"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":319,"cache_read_input_tokens":315325,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":319},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"c279a989-3cd4-4ada-bf47-1336f9108a51"