{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TBecwnepAiq4BVC3NaJtvx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"A_MAX=200 (way too small), B_MAX=50000 (too large — norms grow with b). And still only 5 relations.\n\nThe issue is fundamentally that the NFS search space for 30-digit numbers is too small to generate enough relations. The theoretical advantage of NFS only manifests for LARGE N (>100 digits) where the L[1/3] exponent beats L[1/2].\n\nFor 30-digit N, the NFS advantage in per-candidate yield (2.63x for d=5) is offset by the SMALLER search space (limited by norm growth). The total number of relations is:\n\n\n- yield_per_candidate × search_space_size\n- NFS: 0.7% × (200 × 200) = 280 \n- QS: 0.3% × (100000) = 300\n\nSo they're essentially equivalent. NFS gets better yield per candidate, but that advantage is completely negated by the constrained search space. The crossover point where NFS actually pulls ahead is somewhere around 70-80 digits, where the norm growth becomes slow enough that the larger search space finally outweighs the per-candidate efficiency gain.\n\nI should document this finding properly. Though before I commit, I'm wondering if there's another angle—what if instead of being locked into a single polynomial pair, I could cycle through multiple pairs like SIQS does? That would give me fresh search space for each pair without needing to expand the sieve range. It's more complex to implement and probably won't help much below 70 digits anyway, so I'll focus on documenting what I've found and testing on larger numbers.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":317,"cache_read_input_tokens":321393,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":317},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":