vantage starting around 9 digits, the practical crossover doesn't happen until 70-100 digits once you account for all these implementation costs.\n\nMy experimental data actually confirms this—the NFS variant produces significantly more smooth pairs per candidate at 40 digits, showing the theoretical edge, but the total runtime is still slower than the Quadratic Sieve because of that overhead burden. For our testbed spanning 30 to 100 digits, this means NFS might become viable at the higher end if we can optimize away some of that practical overhead.\n\nRather than attempt a full NFS implementation with all the engineering complexity that entails, I should focus on what's actually feasible: pushing the existing Quadratic Sieve implementations further and carefully documenting how they scale. Looking back at what the project actually requires—finding a novel factoring approach that outperforms existing algorithms—I need to acknowledge that no classical method beats the L[1/3] complexity class, and most optimizations just tweak constants rather than fundamentally changing the game. The best path forward is to thoroughly document these findings and continue with targeted improvements.\n\nNow I should check whether the benchmarks have completed running.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1893,"cache_read_input_tokens":338711,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1893},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f16ee78b-ee57-47d2-a561-91e9aefa955b","uuid":"1b777bd1-2dbb-4f40-9f4d-5fe0a004dd47"}
